column1: 68118;instagram;2019-01-20 14:18:42;FALSE;"with dissociative identity disorder back in the public sphere following the release of m. night shyamalan's film 'glass'
column2: we want to use this opportunity to crush misconceptions and myths about did. leading up to the debut of 'split' - the first film in this horror trilogy - we released a public statement renouncing the cruel and obscenely violent portrayal of this very vulnerable population. this time around
column3: we want to not only enthusiastically co-sign the public statement from isst-d president
column5: but also mindfully educate the public — dismantle these harmful characterizations of childhood trauma survivors before they have a chance to take deeper root. you can us help in that mission!

column1: 💙 here is our in-depth article debunking *dozens* of did myths and misconceptions! link in bio

column2: 5-part did series that you can find on any of our social media
column3: or catch the infographics via our ig highlights. together
column4: we can spread this information far and wide and start to undo the harm caused by films/shows/books like this.

column1: please know that we are thinking of all of you — survivors
column3: and loved ones of those with did/osdd alike. we are in this with you
column5: and will never stop fighting to make world see you as you really are: brilliant
column10: and stronger than most can fathom ever having to be. you are also hurting and in need of resources
column12: and love. these fear-instilling portrayals put more barriers in your way that you don't deserve. we plan to keep knocking down many of those barriers and hope many of you will feel compelled to do so alongside us!

column1: i lost my home. i gave up my things. i left a career behind. and embraced a new way of being.
but that didn't make it easier and i cried for months. yes
and when people would ask me what was wrong
column2: i just kept telling them ""i am dying""... because i was.

column1: and once i let that fully happen for me and i accepted the death of so much
column2: i stopped crying.  i stopped mourning my old life.  and i started living again.

column1: so the next time you are going through a cycle of loss and letting go

column1: a weapon that has left physical and emotional wounds...one that is scary as bombs and bullets but invisible.... join me in my journey as we cry for help.... let them know that enough is enough!!! it is time to act!!! silence will not save us!
the future is in our hands👐

column1: invites you to a public meeting on
🌟building on #metoo in indian media: creating safe work spaces for media women🌟
after the flood of revelations of sexual harassment in the media in the latter part of 2018
column2: the rampant violence against women at work
column3: toxic masculinity and systemic gender discrimination were laid bare. the inadequacy of mechanisms of redress
column4: lack of accountability and impunity for perpetrators were repeatedly called out by women journalists
column5: telling their own stories and those of other survivors.

column1: building on the public awareness that these revelations have sparked
column2: this meeting will examine the ground realities of the challenging task of making workplaces safe
column3: and spotlight proactive measures implemented by media houses. journalists
column5: lawyers and educators will speak from their specific areas of expertise.

column1: 68296;instagram;2019-01-20 11:42:58;FALSE;"včera jsem vzal dceru do divadla na vinohradech na hru čarodějky ze salemu. u hry píšou
column2: že není vhodná pro děti do 12 let
column3: a věděli proč. tohle je vážně drama! žádná sranda
column4: syrové až na kost a hlavně podle reálné předlohy. žádná slátanina
column6: ale skutečná historie ameriky z pera arthura millera. člověku vstávají chlupy na ruce a říká si: „to přeci není možný
column7: tak hloupý nemohl být žádný soud! tam chybí důkazy!“ a přitom hloupý prostě byl. stále doufáte
column8: že pravda a rozum zvítězí nad lží a mstou
column10: jak to dopadne. ani já vám to neřeknu. jděte do divadla! uvidíte skvělý výkon tomáše pavelky.

column1: napětí přitom graduje fantastická hudba vladimíra franze. ano
column3: co kdysi kandidoval na prezidenta. hra je tedy skvělá nejen scénářem

column1: jenomže hra není žádnou akademickou exkurzí do historie
column2: má obrovský přesah do dneška. je o tom
column3: jak fanaticky společnost podlehla puritánskému vnímání světa a ďábla vidí ve všem. a kdo chce psa bít
column8: dokud neřekla jména a nevymyslela si údajné viníky. ve snaze o záchranu jmenovala a rozběhlo se další mučení a další vyslýchání nevinných. najednou si řada lidí uvědomila

2. write down your most important tasks - your daily tasks you need to complete during the day

column1: 68350;instagram;2019-01-20 08:46:34;FALSE;"always help the girls and women around you to speak up and be heard 💪 | photographed @womensmarchsydney for @concreteplayground today. truth be told i find it hard to appreciate planned
column3: but the #metoo movement last year brought back shitty memories
column4: and the conversations i’ve had with other women made me realise how widespread the bullshit is (especially for ethnic/diasporic/immigrant women where there’s a whole other layer of complexity involved)
column5: and how lucky i’ve been to have even had the level of agency i have. so i went in solidarity with my younger self and all the non-men in my life. going through the images

column1: 68367;instagram;2019-01-20 09:11:14;FALSE;i can't believe it's been just over a year since my creating communities of care series went live on little red tarot. sometimes i'm afraid that i'll be reiterating these ideas in different ways for the rest of my life because these problems will persist long after i'm gone. but i'm enlivened seeing so many survivors stepping up for other survivors. the support i've been seeing for survivors in the past year and a half was not my reality four years ago when i outed my abuser and rapist. in fact
column2: i've seen leftists with avidly anti-survivor attitudes do 180s recently as they realize that the social capital invested in them will be undermined if they don't turn their shit around in the era of #metoo . good. we won't tolerate the gaslighting any longer: survivors are not to blame for the fracturing of communities that happens after an exposure. no matter how much their anger threatens your value of politeness. that exposure would not have happened if no abuse had occurred in the first place. link to article in bio.;;en;#metoo;;;;;0;;artemisiasolstice;Artemisia Solstice (they/them);;0;False;0;0;0;66;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/c3da6d989ded1559e91b5424b67ee206/5D2651C1/t51.2885-15/e35/49913212_234755380780733_5258397903508204968_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;i can not believe it is been just over a year since my creating communities of care series went live on little red tarot. sometimes i am afraid that i'll be reiterating these ideas in different ways for the rest of my life because these problems will persist long after i am gone. but i am enlivened seeing so many survivors stepping up for other survivors. the support i have been seeing for survivors in the past year and a half was not my reality four years ago when i outed my abuser and rapist. in fact

column1: مردا اگه با دیدنم تحریک میشن خودشونو کنترل کنن. اونا #نگاه نکنن🚫 چرا من خودمو بپوشونم؟؟😒 ➕گفتم: 👈 اگه شدنی بود و میشد نگاه نکنی یا تحریک نشی که بالاخره اونهمه کمپین اعتراضی مثل #metoo و #women_not_object جواب میداد!!

غریزه که دستوربردار نیست!! 👈بعدشم فرض کن یه نفر تصمیم گرفته وزن کم کنه، اگه این فرد رو هر وعده سر سفره‌ای پر از انواع غذاهای خوش‌رنگ و خوش‌مزه😋 قرار بدیم، می‌تونه خودشو کنترل کنه و چیزی نخوره؟؟ بالاخره ناخنکی می‌زنه ... مگر اینکه اراده پولادینی داشته باشه که اینجور آدما کم گیر میان و اگه ارادشونو تقویت نکنن اونا هم خراب میشن. 💢 ⭕️حالا جوونایی رو در نظر بگیر که امکان #ازدواج ندارن و تو #جامعه با انواع تیپ‌های #تحریک‌_کننده مواجه میشن⚡️😟 به نظرت تو چنین شرایطی چقدر می‌تونن خودشونو کنترل کنن و نگاه نکنن ⁉️😥 وقتی شما حریم‌ها رو رعایت نمی‌کنی چطور انتظار داری مردا بتونن هوس‌شون رو کنترل کنن ⁉️😒 مطمئنا #جلوگیری_از_تحریک راحتتر و اجرایی‌تره تا #کنترل_هوس_برافروخته☝️ 📖 برگرفته از کتاب «تربیت جنسی از منظر قرآن و حدیث»، صفحه ۱۵۱ و ۱۵۲

column1: 68388;instagram;2019-01-20 07:51:52;FALSE;"i wish i could truthfully say that i have never thought about giving up. even then
column3: i mostly would wonder if i was the mother she truly needed. am i really cut out for this? until the diagnosis
column4: i had no idea what i was doing wrong. how come nothing i tried would work?

column1: the doubt i had for myself was crushing me and until recently
column2: nothing relieved that pressure. i would slip in and out of depression and unfortunately
column3: my parenting capacity would be reduced because of it. i was tired
column4: lacked consistency and had limited empathy. a perfect combination to make behaviors worse.

column1: although i have survived years of domestic violence and had to work on myself to heal from it
column2: i had to scrape and drag myself to the surface of it to be the mentally healthy mother my child needs. it has been a long journey
column4: but every time i was on my knees
column6: i somehow managed to put myself back together in a new fashion.

column1: i have learned a tremendous amount about myself. the combination of trauma and parenting have a way of shoving the parts of yourself your brain has chosen to ignore
column2: hide away. but it also displays the strength and power you hold
column3: the trick is that you must perceive yourself that way. the bad parts can be true
column5: but the good parts can be true too. i just started to allow myself to think of myself as strong and powerful
column6: and at first it was foreign and forced
column7: it doesn't feel that way anymore.

column1: i know i'm her mother for a reason and we will keep moving forward.

column1: 68412;instagram;2019-01-20 08:11:22;FALSE;"the we story // yesterday women of every kind gathered together at pregnant then screwed live and under the creative direction of campaigner and all round superwoman @pregnant_then_screwed_mum created something magical.
every panellist and host offered something amazing
column2: every woman who attended had her own story that was just as valuable as those told on the stage. there were laughs
column3: so many laughs; and tears of vulnerability
column4: of “me too”; and there was sisterhood the likes of which i think we rarely seen (and that includes @iam_papab).

column2: and i mean every single woman there
column3: created something that will make a difference. of that i have no doubt. women were inspired
column6: better prepared and armed for whatever fight they need to fight. we united.

column1: my daughter asked me in bed this morning what all the women on the stage were doing and i attempted to explain. she said “well that sounds boring”
column2: so instead i bottom-lined it in a way her five year old brain could comprehend. “we were changing the world for you
column3: so you don’t have to worry or face all the things that mummies currently do. “that’s good
column5: she said. not all of our babies know why we’re doing this
column6: they’re too young to get it but one day they will

column1: 68430;instagram;2019-01-20 06:57:07;FALSE;"this is my story. this is “for myself.”

column2: someone i trusted and held very dearly to my heart took advantage of me in ways i will never be able to forget. it was not until the past few months that i felt brave enough to confront my assaulter and to share my story through one of my forms of therapy. dance. though it has been 6 long years of grieving and healing
column3: i finally feel that i am going to be okay. i wish more than anything that i could have marched today in support of my strong fellow females
column4: but i thank everyone who has been involved in this movement for inspiring me and making me feel brave enough to speak up and use my voice to share my story and to help others who have been in similar situations. @kylelivsey thank you for being the greatest partner with this dance and for your love
column6: and artistic beauty that helped me create such a meaningful piece and helped me heal in ways i didn’t know i needed. @iiswhoiis thank you for writing about your truth and giving other survivors an anthem. i hate that these horrible incidents happen to many people out there
column7: but none of us are alone. we are strong and beautiful and are called survivors for a reason. #metoo #timesup";;en;#metoo

column3: i try my very best to be prepared.  there is a famous trainer that likes to say that preparation isn’t half the battle
column4: it is the battle.  i find this to be so true.  when i meal prep or at least write down what is for dinner this week
column5: it’s just easier.  i don’t have to think about things
column6: it’s there right in front of me. all i have to do is just cook it or heat it up.

column2: you can get meal prep apps
column4: or you can even print out a meal prep calendar. i like to use this weekly planner for my meals.  it was $4 at target.  it’s cute
column5: easy and i just write in the meals for the week and then i know what to buy at the grocery store.  i do allow myself a day where i eat less clean.  you know
column9: i do keep it to clean eating for 6 days a week.  this is just a little tool that helps keep me on track with my diet. .

column1: 68462;instagram;2019-01-20 05:53:49;FALSE;"this happened one year ago. i got assaulted in vancouver. i can’t believe it’s been a year
column2: and i have grown leaps and bounds. i was reeling from my young cousins passing. not paying attention and went for a walk with ear buds in music playing. end result was an  broken cheek and a hairline fracture in my right side jaw. there were worse pics. i post this as a reminder. today i was marching with our sisters/ men who all stood in solidarity at our 3rd annual women’s march. it reminded me to be way more vigilant when out walking and keep at least one ear bud out. remind our sisters

column1: 68475;instagram;2019-01-20 06:04:41;FALSE;"walking in the women’s march today really inspired me to open up the conversation about sexual assault
column2: rape and violence against women (among other things) + it ended with a little dance party! several women (including trans
column3: woc & non binary people) spoke about their experiences which was nothing short of undeniable bravery
column4: courage and inspiration. as someone who has recently come to terms with being a victim of sexual assault
column5: i’ve found that speaking out and opening myself up to the support and love of friends and family in this time has (fortunately) made processing and healing that much easier. of course there is no pressure whatsoever to speak about your own experiences (or broadcast them!) but if you do feel you want to
column6: please feel free to send me or someone you love & trust a message
column7: even if it’s just for a hug or a shoulder to cry on! you’re not alone
column8: you are supported and loved! & for men
column9: take the time to inwardly or outwardly express gratitude for the women in your life because i’m sure you’d be very different without them! call out others’ behaviour and hold each other accountable for actions like cat calling/rape jokes/“unintentional/casual” groping etc.! power to all! love & light ❤️

column1: 68524;instagram;2019-01-20 05:32:46;FALSE;"this may look like just a sign to you - but to me
column2: it was the first time i stood up and said i am a survivor of sexual assault. i’ve written about it on my blog and that was heavy. but carrying this today felt like i was finally speaking my truth out loud. it’s just a piece of (gorgeous pink) paper but it felt powerful to walk with thousands of women and own what i’ve been through in a very public way. i am proud of myself for continuing to talk about something that has greatly affected my life. it isn’t a story i’ve actually told in great detail out loud. but i matter. my story matters. and hearing other women say me too today
column3: sharing looks of solidarity - that inspires me to continue to use my voice for others so that one day women don’t have to say me too

column1: 68564;instagram;2019-01-20 03:34:06;FALSE;"i talk about abuse because it happened to me. and i talk about it because it can happen to you — or to someone you know — or it may already be happening or has happened.
abuse is common. it doesn’t just show up in romantic relationships. i’ve had abusive bosses and abusive friends.
the more you educate yourself on their tactics
column2: the more you can set boundaries and work to emotionally protect yourself. if you are like i was
column7: and angry without realizing why you are experiencing those intense emotions.

column1: best way to figure out if someone is abusive is to see what beliefs they have about things. if you listen to them — really listen — that’s when you’ll see things that stand out.

listen for whether or not they sound entitled. listen for indications that they are the centre of the universe in every story and they fail to see other perspectives. listen for signs that they believe they are superior to everyone else around them. it’s beliefs like those that lead to abusive behaviour.
what we believe dictates how we act.

column1: why so blue? some would say.
i've no recourse but to except these days.
while others prepare feasts and smile and chat
i sit alone pondering my circumstance.
heaven knows how hard i've prayed but these haunted memories won't fade away.
words were spoken that can never be taken back.
a horrible feeling when one is being attacked.
what does it matter they all state.
stand tall and proud and smile so bright that no one will ever know you've lost your inner light.
when the ones you love have all turned their backs and stated firmly

column2: a pathetic ruin that's done nothing right.

column1: you're helpless and fragile and timid with fright.
we won't sugar coat our words of disdain but continue to destroy any hope that you've gained.
still they raise their glasses and cheer. down the rabbit hole alice! they scream and they lear!
i hold on to a world that's now quickly spinning and have dreadful thoughts and suicidal feelings.

column2: no one can see what they have done.

column1: 68625;instagram;2019-01-20 03:44:57;FALSE;"i attended the woman’s march in dc with my sister today - it was filled with passionate and empowered speeches by amazing speakers including many indigenous women and people whose families are being affected by the government shutdown.

it was a smaller march than the previous two years have been in chicago - and it’s sad that there is controversy surrounding anti-semitism with some of the groups leaders.  i hope things can be worked out and handled properly as soon as possible. i know personally how media can spin things or take things out of context
column2: so while i don’t know the whole story behind these anti-semitic accusations
column3: i do know that a few people do not represent the millions who are out fighting for human rights
column4: who are inspiring women to run for office and make real change.

column1: just to name a few things that have happened since the first match: a record # of 131 women are in the 116th congress. democrats deb haaland and sharice davids became the first native american women elected to congress. kyrsten sinema became the first openly bisexual senator and the first female senator from arizona. kristi noem became south dakota’s first female governor. ilhan omar and rashida tlaib became the first muslim women elected to congress. republican marsha blackburn became tennessee’s first female senator. danica roem of virginia is the first openly transgender person elected as state legislator.

column2: the #metoo movement jump started a conversation about sexual harassment and assault
column3: and began the important process of holding accountable men who had been abusing their power for too long.

column1: this movement has been important in so many ways - please continue to support the rights of all humans on this planet - stop trying to find ways to divide those trying to do good. we’ve accomplished some great things but still have a long way to go.

68655;instagram;2019-01-20 03:04:03;FALSE;although i could not attend this years #womensmarch , here are some reminders: no means no. love does not equal consent. trans rights are human rights. black lives matter. immigrants make america great. my body my choice. homosexuality is not a choice but homophobia is. love is love. families have risked their lives seeking asylum in this country, only to have their kids ripped out of their arms when met with guards. it is unbearable & grotesque. we must not be divided on the universal human call to keep families together. we can not be people who take children. “how human are we to standby and do nothing? no more moments of silence, we need moments of change. something bad shouldn’t happen to someone you know in order for you to stop caring, for you to take stance. stop using ownership to justify your voice, stand up for people, because people are people.” representation matters. the way we design our spaces matters. what we do after today matters. regardless, if you went to the women’s march or you didn’t that’s not what’s important. it’s what you do next and how you bring this work into your everyday life that really counts. the resistance must be diverse, intersectional, and inclusive or it is nothing. you have a voice for a reason, use it! and if they don’t want to hear you, speak louder!! ✊🏼✊🏿✊🏽✊🏻✊🏾 #intersectionalfeminist column2: i marched for the #위안부할머니 (“ianfu grandmothers” in korean) who were forced into sexual slavery by the imperial japanese army during wwii. here are 54 of those who came forward as former ianfu (“comfort women”) and fought all their lives to let their stories be heard since the first allegation in 1991. only a small fraction of them are still with us today. i wanted to give them presence abroad at this year’s women’s march in nyc
column3: because they represent the struggle endured by all victims of sexual violence around the world. in short
column4: this isn’t just a “korea issue.” by recognizing this
column5: i also stand for other comfort women survivors from china
column8: for vietnamese women who were raped by korean and u.s. soldiers during the vietnam war
column11: and undocumented women who suffer the highest rate of forcible sexual assault and marginalization on a daily basis across the united states
column12: and for lgbtqia+ people who are too often left out of this conversation. to be a “feminist” is to listen to and act in solidarity with those who are silenced and displaced and to help prevent the cancellation of their voices. with that kind of spirit
column13: i hope the women’s march organizations find a way to overcome the ongoing divisions and recover unity for next year.

column1: 68771;instagram;2019-01-20 01:22:49;FALSE;"the life of someone living with cptsd can be somewhat of a daily battle and extremely debilitating. things that feel normal to most people feel like a massive task for someone suffering anxiety driven by the adrenalin pumped at a higher level through our bodies. our minds mulling over the 101 most serveer possibil scenarios of what can go wrong just with one task. i will be writing a book outlining my time filming with ghosthunter documentary
column2: the behind the scenes of my own mind
column3: through filming and my first screenings and questions and answers
column5: . i may appear strong but deep down i'm a mess faking it till i make it. it's all for a cause i keep telling myself
column6: and if i want change i must step outside my comfort zones. never be stuck in the mind set of how your feeling because only you can drive your mind for greatness. xo love and light xoxox @ghosthunterthemovie

column3: and all the feels this week. posted this journal entry from earlier in the day. i’m feeling much better now
column4: but keeping it real about how it comes & goes. i’ll start with the positives today!

column1: 🌱my therapist is back!! first time i have seen her since late october. 💗
🌱 third #emdr session went well. i continue to really like her. i disclosed the incident with my uncle in detail. i’m really proud that i did that
column2: especially after only seeing her for a few sessions. that would never have happened a year ago. 🌱 i got my first “workout” in post surgery. it was so difficult to take it easy
column3: but i did. i walked for 10 minutes and did the elliptical for 5 mins. it felt so good to get out of the house and moving.

column1: 🌱 family day at home & a three day weekend 💗
🌱 did some self compassion work this week
🌱 haven’t restricted in five days (that’s also a positive)
column2: but i feel raw and vulnerable and want to run right back to it. *sigh* one meal at a time tho. 🌱 dreams have been a bit better

column1: 🌱 the thing that’s the hardest about eating stuff is that i feel like as soon as i eat
column2: i start worrying about the next meal. 🌱my husband scheduled an impromptu pizza party. his family focuses on weight a lot. i’m so glad i reached out to my therapist via email for tips (prior to the party). today would have been my go to restricting day- especially after emdr disclosure and his family. but so far so good. one more meal to go. 😭🤦🏻‍♀️";;en;#emdr;;;;;0;;a_courageously_recovered_life;;;0;False;2;0;0;17;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/107921e301bd70f4d88f5fde8f3d50db/5D28B426/t51.2885-15/e35/50587539_1680833422016845_7851413805530948422_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"hey 👋 lots of positives

column1: 68796;instagram;2019-01-20 00:47:07;FALSE;"#ripjohncoughlin where do i begin?  i sit here and i think about that time i told randy i was tired and he made me do laps with my arms over my head and you started laughing so randy told you to join me.  side by side #doublesalchow because we thought double jumps were so cool.  when it was time to compete
column2: you were right there cheering us all on.  we were so young but we were the best of friends.  i loved you and still do 23 years later.  last night while i was celebrating i received the call i never wanted to receive.  you had committed #suicide.  john
column3: your life had been taken from you before you took it yourself.  the public took a #metoo allegation against you without facts
column5: and spread such hate.  shame on #usfsa and #safesport for their punishment without #dueprocess.  you all have the blood on your hands of my friend!  since when did we become a country where you are guilty when accused?  i fear for all young men and adult men because you will never be able to save yourself or your name.  johns coach wrote it best: ""yesterday i received the most numbing
column7: and heartbreaking call!!!!!!!!! it has taken me all night to grasp and accept. my heart aches incredibly to know john took his life yesterday. his family
column9: and i lost a very special man who lived his life with integrity and kindness. we definitely lost one of the good guys. john was my student
column10: like one of my own children
column11: was an amazing ambassador for our sport
column13: and a great role model. he was driven to help our sport grow

column1: 68935;instagram;2019-01-19 23:38:37;FALSE;"this is another recent thought🧠that i've turned into a writing piece.

the point of the whole metoomovement is to show a sign of courage and bravery to share stories and just to get personal experiences across. to possibly inspire others to do the same.the metoo movement is a way to let others know that everyone faces some kind of pain and some kind of abuse and it is okay to speak out about what you've been through to share your truth. it is also to be brave enough to let your abusers know that what they've did was wrong. admitting to being traumatized is hard to do because everyone wont believe you. in most cases the victims are always victimised but it isn't their faults. the abusers are at fault. abuse is very serious and it is also difficult to discuss. but that's the whole purpose of the metoo movement which is to talk about the struggles you had to overcome from a toxic individual so you could get through it and to motivate others that they could get through it and to give an ""its okay signal"" that its perfectly fine to share their stories and their truth as well.";;en;#metoomovement

column2: we'll fall for anything."" i stand for women's rights and i want banks to understand why i am so passionate

column1: i believe dissent is patriotic. to desire change is healthy. to feel anger can also be healthy
column2: even if it feels uncomfoable. anger can stem from love. when we care
column4: or have compassion for others who are not treated right: that teaches us about our boundaries
column6: and can help us take a stand for what we feel would make others lives better. anger and protesting can be pa of that process. .

column1: for the past two years the women’s march has been a favorite day of feminine pride
column5: and dare i say unity.  i have marched in la and santa ana with my youngest daughter while my oldest has marched in new orleans.  i have felt connected to my daughters. not leading but learning from each other.

column1: this year was already going to be different.  my youngest wanted to head back east for school to be back in time to march in dc with friends.  which is so cool but she was definitely taking some of my enthusiasm with her.
and then....the controversy.  the accusation that the national chapter of the women’s march is anti-semitic.  and since we are talking about that
column2: let’s bring up their mis-step their first year of not including the anti-abortion women.  now what?

column1: i watched bob bland and tamika mallory
column3: face questions about the controversy on the view.  what i expected: denial
column6: acknowledgement that aligning with louis farrakhan was a mistake.  what we got instead: 1) some denial
column7: 2) clarification that the national chapter in no way embraces and anti-semitic ideology
column8: 3) an apology to the jewish community who was feeling hurt.  but all of that was overshadowed by ms.mallory’s almost defiant refusal to denounce mr. farrakhan or even some of the anti-semitic things that he has said (she didn’t support them either - she just didn’t denounce) it was painful to watch.  instead of wrapping it all up with a bow and making it easy for those of us who have loved this movement to unquestionably make our posters and women’s march plans
column9: we were now faced with a dilemma- to march or skip this year.

column1: my interest was dwindling.  but my daughter continued to solidify her plans.  she was definitely heading to the capitol with her jewish and catholic friends - marching in unity.
